    explanation: 'Two layered controls would have significantly limited or prevented this specific incident. First, bulk export restrictions: a support agent\'s account should not be capable of downloading 40,000 customer records in a single operation — this privilege far exceeds what is required for individual customer service interactions. Least privilege applied at the data layer (limiting query scope, maximum export sizes, requiring supervisory approval for bulk operations) would have made mass exfiltration technically impossible with a support account. Second, MFA: even if the attacker successfully obtained the agent\'s password through social engineering, MFA would require the physical second factor (the agent\'s registered device or authenticator app) to log in — stopping the attack at the authentication stage. Firewall upgrades protect the network perimeter but do not prevent a legitimately authenticated user from downloading data. Internal email encryption addresses data in transit, not access control. Frequent customer password resets are irrelevant — the compromise was a staff account, not customer credentials. Together, these two controls exemplify layered defence: limiting both probability and blast radius. Review: Module 4 — Slide 5.',
