    explanation: 'This scenario illustrates a classic multi-stage attack chain — and critically, it succeeded because multiple independent defensive controls were absent simultaneously. Defence-in-depth means that even if one control fails, others should stop the attacker\'s progression. The specific gaps: (1) Staff awareness training — the developer should recognise that unsolicited recruitment contacts with document links are a known spear-phishing vector, especially targeting engineers with valuable system access; (2) Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR) — should have detected and blocked the malware installation before it completed; (3) Secrets management — passwords and API keys must never be hardcoded in source code; they should be injected through environment variables or a secrets vault (HashiCorp Vault, AWS Secrets Manager) that requires separate authentication; (4) Environment separation — a developer\'s account should never have direct access to production systems; staging/development environments should be isolated from live customer data. Firewall upgrades alone would not have stopped this social-engineering-initiated attack. Attributing the entire breach to individual developer error ignores systemic organisational failures in security architecture. Review: Module 2 — Slide 6.',
