    correct: 2,
    explanation: 'GDPR Article 3 establishes explicit extra-territorial scope — it applies to any organisation that processes personal data of individuals located in the EU, regardless of whether the organisation is established in the EU or has a physical office there. A HK-based digital wallet serving even a small number of EU residents is fully subject to GDPR for those individuals\' data. The key criterion is whether the organisation targets EU residents (e.g., offers services in EUR or EU languages) or monitors their behaviour. Simultaneously, PDPO Cap. 486 applies to all personal data of HK residents processed by any organisation. Both regulatory frameworks can impose penalties independently and concurrently: GDPR fines of up to €20 million or 4% of global turnover alongside PCPD enforcement notices and legal liability under PDPO Section 66. The 72-hour breach notification to EU supervisory authorities under GDPR Article 33 is mandatory but does not create exemption from fines — regulators still assess whether the breach resulted from inadequate security measures. Under-resourced compliance programmes that prepare only for PDPO while ignoring GDPR exposure represent a material risk management failure. Review: Module 3 — Slide 4.',
