    correct: 1,
    explanation: 'Designing for multi-regulatory compliance requires three simultaneous architectural principles: (1) Data minimisation — collect only the data strictly required for each specific, documented purpose; surplus data creates surplus liability. GDPR Article 5(1)(c) and PDPO DPP1 both require proportionality. (2) Separation of sensitive data categories — PCI DSS requires cardholder data to be isolated in a hardened Cardholder Data Environment (CDE) with strict access controls, separate audit logs, and network segmentation from other systems. Mixing payment card data with behavioural analytics data in a single database expands PCI DSS scope unnecessarily. (3) Field-level encryption for specific sensitive attributes — PII fields (name, address, ID number) and PCI-scoped data (PAN, CVV) should be encrypted at the field level with separate key management, so that database-level compromise does not automatically expose clear-text sensitive data. Geographic co-location of PCI and personal data in one region does not simplify compliance — it expands the blast radius of any compromise. NoSQL databases have no inherent security advantage over relational databases. "Operational efficiency" that creates a single point of catastrophic failure for 100% of customer data is not a sound risk trade-off. Review: Module 4 — Slide 4.',
