    explanation: 'The gap identified is both log retention policy failure and lack of real-time detection capability. A Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system addresses both dimensions: (1) Centralised, immutable log storage ensures logs cannot be deleted by attackers who compromise individual application servers — forensic evidence is preserved regardless of the compromise scope; (2) Minimum 12-month retention satisfies PCI DSS Requirement 10.7 (12 months required, 3 months immediately accessible) and aligns with HKMA SPM TM-G-1 log retention expectations; (3) Real-time correlation and anomaly alerting enables detection of unusual patterns — abnormal login times, unusual data access volumes, off-hours system queries — that indicate breach activity before damage accumulates to 30 days\' worth. Manual log review by security engineers is not scalable for modern application volumes. Developer self-review of their own application logs is a governance failure — developers should not be reviewing their own systems\' security logs. Disabling logging to reduce storage costs eliminates the only post-breach source of truth, making investigation impossible and regulatory reporting inaccurate. Review: Module 4 — Slide 5.',
