    correct: 2,
    explanation: 'Transparent, rapid breach notification consistently produces materially better outcomes across multiple measured dimensions. Research and regulatory guidance concur: (1) Customer retention — PwC (2023) found customers distinguish sharply between companies that notified them quickly and honestly (allowing protective action) versus those that delayed; the former see lower abandonment rates post-incident; (2) Regulatory treatment — PCPD and EU data protection authorities explicitly consider the speed and transparency of notification in determining whether enhanced penalties apply; delayed disclosure is treated as an aggravating factor; (3) Brand credibility — when Company B\'s delayed disclosure eventually becomes public, the delay itself becomes a second major news story, generating renewed media scrutiny and a second round of customer abandonment; (4) Litigation exposure — delayed notification that prevents customers from taking protective action can be construed as exacerbating harm, increasing civil liability. Rapid notification does not guarantee immunity from fines — regulators still assess the root cause security failures. But it is the single most powerful lever available to management to preserve customer relationships and demonstrate organisational integrity during a crisis. Review: Module 4 — Slide 5.',
