    explanation: 'A compelling board-level cybersecurity investment case requires financial quantification, not compliance obligation alone. The expected value framework: if there is a 15% annualised probability of a significant breach and IBM\'s average breach cost for financial services is US$6.08 million (2024), expected annual loss = US$912,000. Over a 5-year investment horizon, undiscounted expected loss equals US$4.56 million — already approaching the investment cost. Add tail-risk quantification: GDPR fines up to €20 million or 4% of revenue represent catastrophic uninsured exposure. Add IBM\'s control-specific savings: organisations with strong Incident Response Plans save US$2.66 million per breach versus those without; Zero Trust deployments save US$2.22 million; Security AI saves US$2.22 million — each individually could exceed the HK$5M investment cost in expected value saved from a single incident. "It\'s the law" is accurate but persuades boards to do the minimum required, not the appropriate amount. Competitive benchmarking has no quantified return. Framing security as a business development function — protecting the revenue stream and customer trust that Business Development generates — is both accurate and strategically compelling in board context. Review: Module 3 — Slide 5.',
