    explanation: 'This scenario is the classic presentation of a ransomware attack. Ransomware is a category of malware that encrypts victim files or systems and demands payment — typically in cryptocurrency such as Bitcoin or Monero to obscure payment traceability — in exchange for a decryption key. Ransomware has become one of the most financially damaging cyber threats: IBM (2024) reports that ransomware breaches average US$4.91 million in total costs, excluding any ransom payment. The most dangerous vector is human-initiated: Verizon DBIR (2024) found 67% of ransomware attacks begin with phishing emails or exploited credentials. Planned maintenance windows are scheduled in advance with company communication — they do not arrive as surprise demands for cryptocurrency. Credential stuffing attacks target the login layer and focus on data theft, not system lockdown. Physical breaches affect hardware and physical access, not all-system encryption. For a digital wallet operator, ransomware represents both a data confidentiality threat (attackers typically exfiltrate data before encrypting it for double-extortion) and business continuity threat. Paying the ransom does not guarantee decryption and funds future attacks. Offline and immutable backups tested regularly are the primary defence. Review: Module 2 — Slide 4.',
