    explanation: 'As of the current PDPO (Cap. 486), Hong Kong does not impose a fixed statutory breach notification timeframe equivalent to GDPR\'s 72-hour requirement. The Privacy Commissioner for Personal Data (PCPD) strongly encourages voluntary breach notification as soon as reasonably practicable after discovery, and has issued a voluntary notification mechanism since 2015. This distinguishes HK\'s regulatory approach from the EU\'s mandatory regime under GDPR Article 33. However, this does not mean organisations can delay indefinitely: the PCPD\'s enforcement discretion, potential civil liability, and the business imperative of customer trust all incentivise prompt notification. Additionally, HK-based organisations serving EU residents must comply with GDPR\'s 72-hour mandatory notification for breaches affecting EU data subjects. It is also important to note that legislative reform is ongoing in Hong Kong — proposed PDPO amendments may introduce mandatory notification requirements. For GDPR-covered organisations, the 12-hour option is merely best practice, not a requirement; 72 hours is the regulatory threshold. In board-level risk planning, treat notification as a speed-and-transparency exercise, not a compliance minimum. Review: Module 1 — Slide 5.',
