    options: ['A legitimate emergency payment request — process it to avoid business disruption','Business Email Compromise (BEC) — verify the identity of the requester through a separate, pre-established communication channel before processing','A DDoS attack disguised as a financial request','SQL injection via email content'],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: 'This scenario is a textbook Business Email Compromise (BEC) attack — one of the most financially damaging cyber fraud types globally. FBI Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3) data shows BEC attacks generated US$2.9 billion in reported losses in 2023 alone. BEC attackers register lookalike domains (e.g., companyname.net instead of companyname.com), spoof email display names, and combine social engineering (urgency, authority impersonation, unavailability of the "sender") to pressure finance staff into processing unauthorised transfers. The correct response is always to verify through a completely separate, independently established channel — call the CEO\'s known mobile number directly, not a number provided in the suspicious email. "The CEO is traveling" is a deliberate element of the attack designed to prevent verification. For digital wallet operators holding large transaction volumes, BEC protection requires: (1) financial transaction verification policies requiring dual authorisation for payments above threshold; (2) out-of-band confirmation via voice call for any new vendor payments; (3) domain similarity monitoring; and (4) staff training on recognising urgency/authority manipulation tactics. Never process an urgent, high-value transfer without verified identity confirmation. Review: Module 2 — Slide 2.',
