    explanation: 'This is a malicious insider threat — a current or former employee, contractor, or business partner who intentionally uses their legitimate system access to steal, sabotage, or compromise data for personal gain, competitive advantage, or external sale. Malicious insider threats are distinguished from negligent insider threats (accidental data exposure through carelessness, as in the "emailing data to personal Gmail" scenario) by the element of intent. A terminated employee copying customer data before departure has commercial value in data broker markets — full customer databases from FinTech companies are highly sought by competitors, criminal groups, and data brokers. IBM Ponemon Institute (2024) found the average cost of a malicious insider incident is US$4.99 million, notably higher than negligent insider incidents. This scenario underscores the importance of: (1) immediate access revocation upon serving termination notice, not waiting for the last day; (2) USB drive and removable media controls requiring IT authorisation; (3) DLP (Data Loss Prevention) systems monitoring for large database query volumes; (4) Privileged Access Management (PAM) for database administrators. HKMA SPM TM-G-1 specifically addresses insider threat controls. Review: Module 2 — Slide 3.',
