    section_ref: 'Module 4 — Slide 6: Penetration Testing & Security Assessment',
    question: 'What is the primary business purpose of conducting a penetration test (pen test) on your digital wallet platform?',
    options: ['To replace the need for security certifications like ISO 27001','To have authorised security experts simulate real attacks to identify exploitable vulnerabilities before genuine attackers do','To test whether the platform can handle high traffic volumes without performance degradation','To automatically patch all security vulnerabilities found in the scan'],
    correct: 1,
    explanation: 'A penetration test is an authorised, controlled simulation of a real cyberattack conducted by specialist security professionals to proactively identify exploitable vulnerabilities, misconfigurations, and security weaknesses before genuine attackers discover them first. The fundamental principle is "find it before they do." A pen test goes materially beyond automated vulnerability scanning: skilled testers chain multiple low-severity findings together to achieve significant compromise, reproduce attacker reasoning and creativity, and identify logical flaws that automated tools cannot detect. HKMA CFI 2.0\'s iCAST programme is built on intelligence-led penetration testing for licensed institutions. PCI DSS Requirement 11.4 mandates penetration testing at least annually and following significant changes to the cardholder data environment. Pen testing does not replace ISO 27001 certification — they serve complementary purposes (ISO 27001 certifies management system processes; pen tests validate technical control effectiveness). Performance ("load") testing verifies scalability, not security. Pen test findings are reported with remediation recommendations — testers do not automatically patch vulnerabilities. For digital wallet operators, annual penetration testing of the mobile application, API layer, and backend infrastructure should be non-negotiable. Review: Module 4 — Slide 6.',
