    options: ['The card brands (Visa/Mastercard) cover all costs','The affected cardholders pay a small replacement fee','The breached merchant/processor must reimburse card issuers, with amounts can reach millions of dollars under PCI DSS liability frameworks','There is no standardised liability framework — each case is negotiated individually'],
    correct: 2,
    explanation: 'Under PCI DSS contractual liability frameworks administered by card network brand rules (Visa\'s Global Compromised Account Recovery programme and Mastercard\'s ADCR programme), a breached merchant or payment processor that was found non-compliant with PCI DSS at the time of the breach is typically contractually liable to reimburse issuing banks for card reissuance costs and, in some cases, operational fraud losses. Card reissuance costs range from approximately US$3 to US$10 per card. For 400,000 cards, reissuance alone could reach US$1.2 million to US$4 million — before accounting for operational fraud losses, network fines, and post-breach forensic assessment fees. Card brands also impose direct fines on acquirers (who pass them to merchants) for PCI DSS non-compliance discovered in connection with a breach, ranging from US$5,000 to US$100,000 per month. Card brands do not absorb these costs — their liability frameworks specifically exist to protect issuing banks through contractual liability assignment to the breached party. Understanding this contractual exposure is essential for board-level risk quantification on digital wallet platforms processing high payment card volumes. Review: Module 3 — Slide 4.',
