    explanation: 'The Medibank Private breach illustrates the evolution from first-generation ransomware (encrypt and demand payment) to modern "double-extortion" ransomware (encrypt AND exfiltrate sensitive data, then threaten public publication if ransom is refused). This evolution fundamentally changes the risk calculus for operators with sensitive customer data. Traditional advice of "maintain offline backups" allowed organisations to restore encrypted systems without paying ransom. Double-extortion attacks nullify this strategy: even if Medibank had fully restored from backups within hours, the 9.7 million records were already exfiltrated and were subsequently published on the dark web in chunks starting in November 2022. For FinTech digital wallet operators, the Medibank lesson translates directly: customer financial records, identity documents, transaction histories, and biometric templates are equally high-value exfiltration targets. Ransomware defences must include: (1) network segmentation to limit lateral movement before exfiltration occurs; (2) Data Loss Prevention (DLP) monitoring for large out-bound data transfers; (3) Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR) to detect ransomware deployment before encryption begins; (4) offline backups — necessary but no longer sufficient alone. Review: Module 5 — Slide 5.',
