    correct: 1,
    explanation: 'Network segmentation is the practice of dividing a computer network into distinct subnetworks (segments), each isolated from others by firewall rules and access controls, so that a compromise of one segment does not automatically grant access to others. In this scenario, the marketing website — a relatively low-security, internet-facing asset — was on the same flat network as the customer database server (a high-security, crown-jewel asset). A hacker compromising the website therefore gained unrestricted network access to the database through lateral movement, a technique attackers use to navigate from an initial entry point to high-value targets within the same network. Proper segmentation would require the hacker to also breach the network boundary between the DMZ (demilitarised zone for internet-facing services) and the internal data tier — a separate, harder barrier. PCI DSS mandates network segmentation between the Cardholder Data Environment (CDE) and all other systems. HKMA CFI 2.0 references network zoning as a core control. Antivirus protects the compromised server but not the database reached through the network. Segmentation limits the blast radius — even successful initial compromises produce bounded damage. Review: Module 4 — Slide 3.',
