    correct: 1,
    explanation: 'Backup integrity requires backup isolation — the ability of the backup copy to survive a catastrophic event affecting the primary system. Ransomware is specifically designed to encrypt all network-reachable drives, including mapped network drives and shares. A backup stored on a networked server within reach of an infected host will be encrypted alongside the primary data, destroying the restore capability that backups are meant to provide. The 3-2-1 backup rule — a widely accepted standard — requires: 3 copies of data, on 2 different storage media types, with 1 copy stored offsite or offline (air-gapped, immutable, or physically isolated). An offline backup on removable media disconnected before the attack, or an immutable cloud backup with write-once-read-many (WORM) enforcement, cannot be reached by network-traversing ransomware. HKMA\'s Business Continuity planning guidance requires documented Recovery Time Objectives (RTO) and Recovery Point Objectives (RPO) and tested restoration procedures. File format is irrelevant to the core failure. Higher backup frequency does not help when the backup itself is compromised. Cloud backups are helpful but must also be configured with immutability and access controls, or they can also be encrypted if the attacker compromises cloud credentials. Review: Module 4 — Slide 5.',
